#N canvas 270 75 955 530 theory_from_example 0;
#X text 20 15 "sinesum" is useful to draw waveforms for a wavetable
oscilator. It generates waveforms by summing sine functions as if they
were sine components of a harmonic series.;
#X text 19 69 The first argument of the "sinesum" command is the table
size (if the table is not set at this size \, it will be resized to
it). After that we have a number of elements that will define the number
of sine components \, from the first element of the harmonic series
and up. The number values are the amplitudes of each sine component
(from 0 to 1). Negative values indicate a phase change of 180 degrees.
;
#X obj 5 216 mtof;
#X obj 136 317 *~;
#X obj 165 230 sequencer 42 40 40 45 40 49 52 52 45 43 43 47 50 54
55 55, f 29;
#X text 464 21 In this example we use [tabosc4~] \, a native object
that uses an array as a waveform. We generate a waveform with the "sinesum"
message sent to an array \, which needs an array size that's a power
of two (512 in this case) and a list of partials (8 of them in this
example)., f 63;
#X text 464 415 Test the resulting sound below with a frequency input
or from a sequencer driving [tabosc4~]., f 63;
#X text 464 176 Note that after sending the list of partials \, we
do normalize the array. A subpatch also normalizes the partials for
us to visualize the normalized values of each partial., f 63;
#X text 464 289 The details about interpolation and guard points are
presented later in this tutorial \, but know for now this interpolation
type uses 4 points - hence the "4" in [tabosc4~]. Also note that none
of this information about extra points is needed for the patch \, this
is just technical details in the background., f 63;
#X text 464 97 Play with the number boxes to the right. Each box represents
the amplitude of a partial from our partials list. The drawn waveform
is composed as a sum of this list of 8 partials. The sinesum message
generates waveforms in arrays from a list of amplitudes for each partial.
The first value is the table size., f 63;
#X text 464 226 Sinesum generates arrays with "extra points" (in this
example \, 512 points plus 3) \, which also called "guard points".
These extra points are needed for interpolation in [tabosc4~] \, so
the 'sinesum' command is specially designed for [tabosc4~]., f 63
;
#X text 464 366 Another detail is that 'sinesum' only generates tables
whose size is a power of two (plus 3 points). So [tabosc4~] can only
read tables with such possible sizes., f 63;
